**UPDATE:** [We've decided to convert this warning into a hard error](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/36889#issuecomment-275166478), but are still waiting for a PR to make that a reality. If you're interested in contributing, [there are directions for writing such a PR available here](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/36889#issuecomment-287145267).

This tracking issue pertains to a bug fix for https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/22889. The problem was that the compiler was accepting two inherent impls that both defined the same method, which creates an obvious ambiguity:

```rust
struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    fn id() {}
}

impl Foo {
    fn id() {}
}
```

The most obvious fix here is to give one method a distinct name, though sometimes there are other possible rewrites (e.g., one could rewrite the impls to use a double dispatch pattern).

#### Current status

- [x] https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/31925 introduces the `overlapping_inherent_impls` lint as warn-by-default
- [x] https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/36894 makes the `overlapping_inherent_impls` lint deny-by-default
- [ ] PR ? makes the `overlapping_inherent_impls` lint a hard error
